        <p>
            <m>{\color{black} \textbf{Key Takeaway:}}</m>
        </p>
         <p>
            A <m>\textbf{triangular prism}</m> is a three-dimensional 
            shape with two triangular faces and three rectangular faces.
        </p>
        <p>
            It belongs to the family of prisms and has a 
            total of <m>5</m> faces,  <m>9</m> edges, and <m>6 </m> vertices.
        </p>
        <p>
            The figure below shows the triangular prism showing the rectangular faces and the rectangular faces.
        </p>
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="Prism1">
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
                % Define points
                \coordinate (A) at (0,0,0);
                \coordinate (B) at (3,0,0);
                \coordinate (C) at (1.5,2,0);
                \coordinate (D) at (0,0,3);
                \coordinate (E) at (3,0,3);
                \coordinate (F) at (1.5,2,3);
                
                % Draw front triangular face
                \draw[very thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
                
                % Draw back triangular face
                \draw[very thick] (D) -- (E) -- (F) -- cycle;
                
                % Connect front and back faces (rectangular sides)
                \draw[very thick] (A) -- (D);
                \draw[very thick,red] (B) -- (E);
                \draw[very thick,red] (C) -- (F);
                \draw[very thick,blue] (D) -- (E) -- (F) -- cycle;
                
                
                % Arrows and Labels
                \draw[-&gt;, thick, blue] (0,-1,0) -- (-1,-3,0) node[left, black] {\huge{\textbf{Triangular face }}};
                \draw[-&gt;, thick, red] (2,1,1.5) -- (1,3,1.5)node[left, black] {\huge{\textbf{Rectangular face}}};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
            
        </image>
        
        <p>
            The total surface area of a triangular prism is the sum of 
            the areas of all the faces of the prism.
        </p>
        <p>
            The rectangular faces are said to be the <m>\textbf{lateral faces}</m>, while the triangular faces are called <m>\textbf{bases}</m>. If the bases of a triangular prism are placed horizontally, 
            they are referred to as the top and the bottom (faces) of the prism, respectively.
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Formula for Surface Area of Triangular Prism}</m>

        </p>
        <p>
            The triangular prism formula for surface area is formed by adding up the area of 
            all the rectangular and triangular faces of a prism.
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Note:}</m> The area of a triangle is, <m>A=\frac{1}{2}bh</m> and for the 
            rectangle is, <m>A=l \times w</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Where, <m>b=\textit{base of the triangle} \,,\,h=\textit{height of the triangle} \, ,\,l=\textit{length of the rectangle} 
            \,\textbf{and}\, w=\textit{width of the rectangle}</m>
        </p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the surface area of the rectangular prism shown.
                </p>
                <image width="40%"> 
                <latex-image label="Prism3">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2]
                        % Define coordinates
                        \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (B) at (4,0);
                        \coordinate (C) at (0,3);
                        \coordinate (D) at (2,4); % Estimated position for D
                        \coordinate (E) at (6,1); % Estimated position for E
                        \coordinate (F) at (2,1.5);


                        % Draw the base triangle ABC
                        \draw [very thick,fill=green](A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
                        \draw [very thick,fill=green](D) -- (E) -- (F) -- cycle;

                        % Draw the dashed lines
                        \draw[dashed,very thick] (D) -- (F);
                        \draw[dashed,very thick] (E) -- (F);
                        \draw[dashed ,very thick] (A) -- (F);

                        % Draw the visible lines to complete the figure
                        \draw [very thick](C) -- (D);
                        \draw [very thick](D) -- (E);
                        \draw [very thick](B) -- (E);

                        % Add right angle symbol
                        \draw [very thick] (0.3,0) -- (0.3,0.3) -- (0,0.3);

                        % Add dimensions
                        \node[below,blue] at (2,0) {\huge{\textbf{4 in}}};
                        \node[left] at (0,1.5) {\huge{\textbf{3 in}}};
                        \node[above right] at (1,2) {\huge{\textbf{5 in}}};
                        \node[below left] at (5,1) {\huge{\textbf{6 in}}};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                    
                </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Surface area}= \textbf{Area of the two triangles} +  \textbf{Area of three triangels}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The sides of the triangular base are: 
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>b_1=3\,in</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>b_2=4\,in</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>b_3=5\,in</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The triangular base is a right triangle, and so the height is one of our sides. We will use <m>h=3\,in.</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The length of the prism is <m>l=6\,in</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Calculate the area of a triangular base using the formula for the area of a triangle: <m>A=\frac{1}{2}bh</m>, where <m>b</m> is 
                    base of the triangle. Multiply this result by 2, since there are two triangular bases with this area. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> A=\amp \frac{1}{2}bh</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{2}\times 4 \times 3</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 6\,in^2</mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Multiplying this by 2, since we have two triangular bases, we have that the area of the bases is: 
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> A=\amp 2 \times 6\,in.^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp {\color{green} 12\,in^2}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Find the area of the rectangular sides. then add the whole area
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> A=\amp (4 \,in \times 6\,in)+(6\,in\times 5\,in)+(3\,in \times 6\,in) </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 24+30+18 </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 72\,in^2 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{Surface area }=\amp  {\color{green} 24\,in^2}+72\,in^2 </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 84 \, in^2</mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
                
             </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the surface area of the triangular prism shown below.
                </p> 
                <image width="40%">
                <latex-image label="Prism4">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8,blue]
                        
                        % Define the coordinates of the vertices
                        \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (B) at (2,0);
                        \coordinate (C) at (1,3);
                        \coordinate (D) at (4,1);
                        \coordinate (E) at (6,1);
                        \coordinate (F) at (5,4);

                        % Draw the front face (triangle ABC)
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;

                        % Draw the back face (triangle DEF)
                        \draw[thick] (D) -- (E) -- (F) -- cycle;




                        % Draw the connecting edges
                        \draw[thick,dashed] (A) -- (D);
                        \draw[thick] (B) -- (E);
                        \draw[thick] (C) -- (F);

                        % Draw the red line for height
                        \draw[red, thick] (1,0) -- (1,3);



                        % Add the dimensions
                        \node[left,rotate=45] at (0.5,2.5) {29 cm};
                        \node[below] at (1,0) {20 cm};
                        \node[ red] at (1.2,1.5) {21 cm};
                        \node[below left] at (5,0) {31 cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                    
                </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Surface area}= \textbf{Area of the two triangles} +  \textbf{Area of three triangels}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                     The area of triangular faces.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Area of a triangular face} =\amp \frac{1}{2}(bh)</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{2}\times 21 \,cm \times 20\,cm </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp  210\, cm^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{Area of two triangular faces}=\amp (2 \times 210)\,cm^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp {\color{blue} 420\,cm^2}  </mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The area of the Lateral faces.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{Surface area}=\amp (20\,cm \times 31\, cm)+(31\,cm \times 21\, cm)+(29\,cm \times 31\, cm) </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 620\,cm^2 +651\,cm^2+899\,cm^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp {\color{green} 2170\,cm^2 }</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefor, <md>
                        <mrow>\text{surface area} = \amp  {\color{blue} 420\,cm^2}+{\color{green} 2170\,cm^2 }</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 2\,590 \,cm^2</mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The total surface area is <m>{\color{black} 2\,590 \,cm^2}</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
